<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Here, the mechanisms of colonial authority are again made evident. It has granted the power for a party of men to be established, paid by public funds, to hunt down and recover John Punch and his accomplices. Also, of note here are the dates. The establishment of this commission has taken around 25 days since the previous petition was submitted to the council, indicating how slow the processes of government administration and control could be in colonial societies.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p style="-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-family:'.SF NS Text';">&lt;br />&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">This paragraph also contains clear indications as to the underlying racial elements of colonial society, with the emphasis being clear on John Punch and others as runaway negroes.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
