<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Unlike his fellow – European – runaways, John Punch was sentenced to a much worse fate. He is ordered here to serve his master for the rest of his natural life. Moreover, this punishment is not limited to Virginia, but extended to everywhere (an indication of the Royal Authority with which these colonial courts were invested).&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p style="-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-family:'.SF NS Text';">&lt;br />&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">This is the true significance of this document. John Punch represents the first known example of legal, African slavery in the North American colonies. No longer an indentured servant, he is now the property – for life – of his master.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
